According to a report by Intel Market Research, the global Compute-In-Memory (CIM) Chip Market was valued at USD 211 million in 2025 and is projected to reach USD 52.37 billion by 2032, registering an exceptional CAGR of 121.7% during the forecast period. The market is witnessing exponential growth as industries increasingly adopt energy-efficient computing architectures to support artificial intelligence, edge computing, and data-intensive workloads while overcoming the limitations of traditional von Neumann architectures.
Compute-In-Memory chips perform computations directly within memory arrays, significantly reducing data transfer, power consumption, and latency. The technology is rapidly gaining traction for AI inference, neural network acceleration, IoT devices, autonomous systems, and edge applications that require high-speed, low-power processing. Continuous advancements in emerging memory technologies such as Resistive RAM (ReRAM), Phase-Change Memory (PCM), and Magnetoresistive RAM (MRAM), along with increasing investments from semiconductor companies and AI startups, are accelerating commercialization of CIM solutions.
